SIMPLE: impair
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impair
<hw>Im*pair"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Impaired</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Impairing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>empair</asp>.]</altsp> <ety>[OE. <ets>empeiren</ets>,
<ets>enpeiren</ets>, OF. <ets>empeirier</ets>, <ets>empirier</ets>, F.
<ets>empirer</ets>, LL. <ets>impejorare</ets>; L. pref. <ets>im-</ets>
in + <ets>pejorare</ets> to make worse, fr. <ets>pejor</ets> worse. Cf.
<er>Appair</er>.]</ety> <def>To make worse; to diminish in quantity,
value, excellence, or strength; to deteriorate; <as>as, to
<ex>impair</ex> health, character, the mind, value</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Time sensibly all things <qex>impairs</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In years he seemed, but not <qex>impaired</qex> by years.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To diminish; decrease; injure; weaken; enfeeble;
debilitate; reduce; debase; deteriorate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impair</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Impair
<hw>Im*pair"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To grow worse; to
deteriorate.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impair</ent>⟦br⟧

